@eric-haibin-lin

I'm wondering if it would be possible / very difficult to allow custom types to have multiple kinds. I often have the issue of having both a "naive" scalar representation and a more complex mapping one.

That might look like for your `Point` exemple:

```yaml
someValue: !point
- 12
- 21
- 42
someIdenticalValue: !point
  x: 12
  y: 21
  z: 42
```

It would be very cool if it was possible either to pass an array for kind instead or simply omit it.

```js
class Point {
  constructor(data) {
    if (!data.x) {
      data = {x: data[0], y: data[1], z: data[2]}

    this.klass = 'Point';
    this.x = data.x
    this.y = data.y
    this.z = data.z
  }

  // …
}

var PointYamlType = new yaml.Type('!point', {
  kind: ['sequence', 'mapping'], // either a sequence or a mapping
  resolve: data => data !== null && (data.x && data.y && data.z || data.length === 3)
  construct: data => new Point(data),
  // …
}
```

It might be a good idea to provide kind as a 2nd argument to allow for safer/cleaner code:

```js
class Point {
  constructor(data) {
    this.klass = 'Point';
    this.x = data.x
    this.y = data.y
    this.z = data.z
  }

  // …
}

var PointYamlType = new yaml.Type('!point', {
  kind: ['sequence', 'mapping'],
  resolve: (data, kind) =>
    data !== null && data.kind === 'sequence' ?
      data.length === 3 :
      data.x && data.y && data.z,
  construct: (data, kind) => {
    if (kind === 'sequence')
      data = {x: data[0], y: data[1], z: data[2]}
    return new Point(data)
  },
  // …
}
```

What would be your thoughts about this?

when navigating a graph, I often use a chain of relations through a recursive function. Maybe its equivalent could be included in the rdflib.Graph methods ?

```python
def chained_values(graph,source,*relations):
    """Follow the path of successive `relations` in `graph`, starting from `source`"""
    if not relations:
        return source
    else:
        r, *rest = relations
        return chained_values(graph, graph.value(source,r) , *rest)
```

this crude code is not robust against multiple paths, though.

Hi all,

Is it useful to have a **layer_norm_dim** (similar to dropout_dim or sum_dim) in addition to layer_norm?
Currently, I tried a naive version (only applied for a matrix input) but it may be slow. 

```
Expression layer_norm_dim(const Expression& x, const Expression& g, const Expression& b, unsigned d){
    std::vector<Expression> vCols(x.dim().d[d]);
    for (unsigned i = 0; i < x.dim().d[d]; i++){ 
        Expression c_x = select_cols(x, {i});
        vCols[i] = layer_norm(c_x, g, b);
    }
    return concatenate_cols(vCols);
}
```

